Department of Social Work | Orientation Visit to Functional Vocational Training and Research Society (FVTRS)

            <b class="panel-title pull-right">July 21<sup>st</sup> 2017</b>
            <div style="clear:both"></div>
        </div>
		<div class="panel-body">
		

            <p align=justify>The Department of Social Work of Kristu Jayanti College, Bangalore has organized an orientation visit for the third semester students to Functional Vocational Training and Research Society (FVTRS) on the 21st of July 2017. The students were guided by <b>Dr. Jonas Richard A., Dr. I. Jerry Richards, Dr. Winnie Joyce A. and Dr. Emmanuel Daniel</b>, faculty members of the Department of Social work. The orientation visit started with a brief session by Mr. Felix D’Souza, Program Co-ordinator, wherein the students were familiarised about the organisation in detail. <b>Mr. Felix</b> spoke about the origin, vision and mission of the agency and various programs and projects undertaken by them. One of the strategies adopted by FVTRS to help the school dropout is by facilitating them to obtain the certificate by pursuing academic studies or by attending skill training in any trade of their choice under the scheme of National Institute of open Schooling (NIOS). The first session came to an end where the students raised their questions and clarifying their queries.</p>
            <p align=justify>Next session was handled by Mr. Philip Mathew, Executive Director, FVTRS where in Sir enlightened upon the concept of development and the various aspects of development.  <b>Mr. Philip</b> also spoke about the different developmental strategies which can be adopted to have a better community in terms of change, progress and growth. Mr. Philip further emphasized on the skill development and net skill training which are being provided for the marginalised sections of the society. The agency prepares and disseminates the skill training and EDP related information and data through IEC materials and organise regional/national level conferences. FVTRS has also initiated an action research on SCOPE (Skilling Community Owned Promotion and Enhancement) which is focusing on a community based approach in skill development, making it a community owned, continuous and sustainable process. The skill training possibilities of youth and tribal areas of Chhotanagpur belt covering the states of Chhattisgarh, Jharkhand and Odisha is the current process of research in which FCTRS is engaged with. The students’ queries were clarified by Mr. Felix and Mr. Philip at the end of the session.</p>
            <p ALIGN=JUSTIFY>The fruitful and effective session came to an end with the vote of thanks by Mr.Philip Mathew where he appreciated the students for choosing MSW. Ms. Sreya Soosan Renji gave the thanksgiving address on behalf of the Department of Social Work, Kristu Jayanti College.</p>




